      "writtenOn": "2020-03-02T05:37:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "In my understanding, the examples in your comment support my arguments, and here is why.\n\nIf an object is created with a New() function that takes a context, I think the lifetime of the created object should be coupled with the lifetime of the context. For example, spanner.NewClient() creates Spanner API clients with the context, it passes the context into its child calls, as following.\n: SessionClient -\u003e APIClient -\u003e grpc.Dial -\u003e grpc.ClientConn.\n\nAt the tail level inside spanner.NewClient(), the grpc.Clientconn is created with the context, and I believe that the lifetime of the connection is coupled with the context.\n\nIf I look at Single() of Spanner Client at https://github.com/googleapis/google-cloud-go/blob/master/spanner/client.go#L291, I think that it uses the session client to execute the query.\n\nIn summary, IIUC, the lifetime of spanner.NewClient() is bound to the lifetime of the context given at the time of creation, and all the subsequent functions performed with the client will fail after the context being closed, because the grpc client channel will be invalid once the context, passed to spanner.NewServer(), is cancelled.\n\ne.g.,\n```\n  clientCtx, cancel :\u003d context.WithCancel(...)\n  client :\u003d spanner.NewClient(clientCtx, ....)\n  cancel()\n  queryCtx :\u003d context.Background()\n  // this should fail, although the query context is still alive,\n  // because the client context has been closed.\n  iter :\u003d client.Single().Query(queryContext, ....)\n```\n\nI can find the same pattern from bigquery.NewClient().\n\nThis is what I tried to describe as confusing.\n\"It\u0027s confusing that the context used to create the server context has no impact the request serving context.\"\nI acknowledge that the following is more accurate statement.\n\"It\u0027s confusing the the context used to create the server context has no impact on Run() and Start()\"\n\n----------------------------------------\nWhat about removing param \"ctx\" from NewServer()?\n\nTBH, I don\u0027t find the value of taking param ctx in NewServer(). It\u0027s only being used to generate the random auth token, but the NewServer() already provides interfaces to let callers control the auth token via ServerConfig. If necessary, the caller can simply pass a custom auth token to NewServer(). There is no reason to take a context to be used for the auth token generator.\n\nThere are two choices.\n(1) NewServer() invokes cryptorand.Read() with context.Background().\n(2) The auth token is generated in Start().\nThe auth token is generate only when the server needs. At the beginning of Start(), the server generates a random auth token with the given context, and Start() will immediately fail if cryptorand.Read(ctx, buf) fails.\n\nI personally prefer (2). Let me know your idea. Thanks",
      "parentUuid": "3540ca01_f0a8fa50",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 15,
        "startChar": 18,
        "endLine": 15,
        "endChar": 32
      },
